Replicating the PCA of a published Study¶

about the assignment¶

For my final project wrapping up 1 quarter of independent study under Edwin Solares. I had to recreate the PCA portion of a paper that was analyzing genomic data.

The paper whose PCA study I chose to replicate was:

High-Density SNP Genotyping of Tomato (Solanum lycopersicum L.) Reveals Patterns of Genetic Variation Due to Breeding

by: Sung-Chur Sim, Allen Van Deynze, Kevin Stoffel, et al.

In [1]:
from IPython.display import Image
Image("./imgs/Figure1.png")
Out[1]:

about the paper¶

The study took a collection of 426 tomatoes (410 inbred & 16 hybrids) and had each of their SNP's genotyped. This meant that they sequenced the tomato's genome, and then identified which nucleotide was present at each of the 7,000+ Single Nucleotide Polymorphism sites further marking which nucleotide came from which parent. Then on this data they performed Principal Component analysis using the SNP sites to verify that the tomatoes could be segregated into their corresponding subpopulations (originally defined from their phenotypes) through this SNP data of each tomato. Then using the variances and contributions they had from each of the SNP sites in their PCA they were able to determine which SNP's were the most influential in segregating the tomatoes into their subpopulation which in turn highlighted the chromosomes and sites of interest as the contributors of the phenotypic differences between the plants. These phenotypic differences were deemed important as these tomatoes have been bred by people from different cultures to achieve these certain traits and understanding the genetic background and function could prove useful while engineering new behaviors in such plants.

The study found that in even inbred tomatoes (tomatoes which when mating with themselves produce perfect clones due to histories of inbreeding) there exists high levels of genetic diversity among the SNP's. They also learned that chromosomes 2, 4, 5, 6, and 11 in particular host the SNP's which explained much of the differences observed in the subpopulations from the PCA's. Through the use of F-tests and studying the Minor Allele frequency patterns they confirmed these regions as influential.

performing the pca¶

This dataset & pca analysis were not very conventional for me, and there was a lot to learn regarding snp data and performing analysis on it.

Here I begin the processing for the 1st PCA graph. I used a table that they referenced from a different paper they published around that time that they said that they used to determine which SNP's to include for their PCA. Note that this is how they got 4,000+ SNPs instead of 7,000+ SNPs in the title of figure 1's PCA's.

I seperate the nucleotides received from each parent as they will need to be mapped seperately during the PCA as there is a difference whether a nucleotide was obtained from the father or the mother. For most of the specimens due to inbreding they have the same nucleotide from both parents but there were instances in which I witnessed a difference between mother & father supplied nucleotides so I wanted to make sure. The mapping of the nucleotides was a simple numeric one. One thing to note is that the mapping will give the nucleotides an order even if it's meaningless for now.

why the PCA is important & what it shows¶

The PCA is important as it allows us to make sense of the vast amount of genomic data that each organism contains and find connections between the genome of organisms in a common species to further understanding the genome of that specific species and identify regions of interest within the species' genome which have phenotypic significance. To put the amount of data that the PCA is able to sift through in a matter of minutes, this SNP table was 400+ organisms with 7000+ dimensions of information which needed to be condensed to 2 dimensions to even visualize. A person cannot begin to fathom processing such data by hand, nor without linear algebra would they know where to start. The PCA is able to sift through this data without much maintenance after processing the data making it a form of unsupervised learning model. This means that it uses the natural distribution of the data for classification and doesn't require any labeled data. For example the subpopulations of the tomatoes need not be labeled for the pca to produce a similar looking plot to the plots above (just without the colors) saving time and resources in other & future applications. Overall the PCA is important as it provides a way to interpret this vast amount of genomic and SNP data regarding the species under study.

Moving away from the importance of the PCA, the analysis shows many important things. The first being that there is a clear correlation between subpopulation of the tomato species and the SNP data obtained from a single genome assembly of the tomato. The groups can even be circled in the graphs produced either by hand or k-means clustering. This distinction might sound obvious on paper, different tomato subspecies have differences in their genetic code and tomatoes from the same subspecies would have fewer differences, but the PCA goes further and says instead of looking at the entire genome we only need to care about ~7000 Single Nucleotide Differences (Polymorphisms). Figure 1B goes further and says that we need to care about fewer SNP's, only about 1100. This means that identifying and targeting these differences in tomato genomes could potentially begin with these specific nucleotides. The paper took the results of the PCA a bit further & identified the exact the SNP's which contributed to the PCA the most & determined which chromosomes that they originated from. Then ran further statistical tests to prove correlations between the SNP's identified and chromosomes. This allows focus to shift from the entire genome to a few specific chromosomes. Also the group mentioned how the SNP's and chromosomes identified subverted their expectations specifically in the case that the largest chromosome didn't contain the most significant SNP's whereas some smaller ones did, provoking the question that are SNP's uniform in significance or are certain chromosomes more responsible than others for subspecies phenotypic differences and to what extent & why?

why I chose this paper¶

The primary motives for pursuing this project were to learn more about the vast and wonderful world of Bioinformatics & complete the course objectives so I can pass this course.

But out of all the papers why one about SNP's in Tomatoes?

Well short story ... Google loaded this paper 1st.

Long story ... My Instructor, Edwin, recomended if we get stuck finding papers we just look up "Rice PCA China" and we will find mountains of papers that we can use. He was right, but I was stubborn. I didn't want to do what everyone else was doing, so I began looking up a whole bunch of different organisms trying to find a good PCA study. Now I knew about PCA all the way from linear algebra and I knew that its true power lay in reducing the dimensions of extremely large datasets to uncover relations and correlations that could not be gleaned by the naked eye or the efforts of a person. When I found papers with tiny datasets (50x20) I looked further for a paper that understood the technique and applied it appropriately and for a problem that needed it. A little while later I looked up "Tomato PCA" and found a really good paper in Nature that included a bunch of data and its processing scripts. I didn't know what SNP was or what most of the words in the paper meant, but I grabbed a table whose rows matched the rows of the resultant PCA & started my analysis hoping to be done with the project fairly quickly. After the PCA was done I knew that I did something horribly wrong as the result I was getting wasn't even close to the results from the paper. I actually needed to understand what they were doing and what was going on. So I go ask Edwin & he confirms my suspicions that I was doing this all wrong. He explains the basics of what SNP's were and how what I thought was the dataset was clearly not the dataset they were referencing. I began looking into the paper and scripts further and I realized that they were doing all the analysis on a different dataset that I didn't have access to that the paper referenced from a different paper (this paper). Looking up that paper I found the SNP dataset, but it was a different format that Edwin had mentioned. At this point I was highly debating if I wanted to enter this rabbit hole or should I just chose a different paper with a smaller dataset & take the easy way out. But that isn't me, I don't run away from problems. I choose to spend too many hours and too much energy overcoming and surpassing adversity. I went through like 3 Bio textbooks (no joke) trying to figure out what format the SNP data was in and how to properly interpret it, what exactly was going on in the paper, and processing the data like the paper with the appropriate filter methods. At this point I was consumed by the challenge of being able to learn something new all by myself & simply repeat what these scientists had done 6 years ago on my laptop.

I initially chose a tomato paper due to my Hubris, but I stuck with it and eventually did my report on this one due to my pride. If I can't pick up things left & right what type of programmer am I, and how do I expect to stay in Bioinformatics?
